07973nam a22008775i 9780226637853DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20082005ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226637853  a(DE-B1597)525094  a(OCoLC)781254185  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHQ799.7 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.2350973a305.242/086/9/0973a305.2420869097300aOn Your Own without a Net :bThe Transition to Adulthood for Vulnerable Populations /ced. by D. Wayne Osgood, Gretchen R. Ruth, Constance Flanagan, E. Michael Foster. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b8 figures, 1 line drawing, 7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation Series on Mental Health and Development00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Why Focus on the Transition to Adulthood for Vulnerable Populations? -- t2. The Transition to Adulthood for Youth “Aging Out” of the Foster Care System -- t3. The Transition to Adulthood for Adolescents in the Juvenile Justice System: A Developmental Perspective -- t4. Policy and Program Perspectives on the Transition to Adulthood for Adolescents in the Juvenile Justice System -- t5. Young Adults Reentering the Community from the Criminal Justice System: The Challenge of Becoming an Adult -- t6. Prisoner Reentry and the Pathways to Adulthood: Policy Perspectives -- t7. Homeless Youth and the Perilous Passage to Adulthood -- t8. Transition for Young Adults Who Received Special Education Services as Adolescents: A Time of Challenge and Change -- t9. Transition Experiences of Young Adults Who Received Special Education Services as Adolescents: A Matter of Policy -- t10. Risks along the Road to Adulthood: Challenges Faced by Youth with Serious Mental Disorders -- t11. Coping with Mental Health Problems in Young Adulthood: Diversity of Need and Uniformity of Programs -- t12. Adolescents with Disabilities in Transition to Adulthood -- t13. Youth with Special Health Care Needs and Disabilities in Transition to Adulthood -- t14. The Transition to Adulthood for Vulnerable Youth and Families: Common Themes and Future Directions -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the decade after high school, young people continue to rely on their families in many ways-sometimes for financial support, sometimes for help with childcare, and sometimes for continued shelter. But what about those young people who confront special difficulties during this period, many of whom can count on little help from their families? On Your Own Without a Net documents the special challenges facing seven vulnerable populations during the transition to adulthood: former foster care youth, youth formerly involved in the juvenile justice system, youth in the criminal justice system, runaway and homeless youth, former special education students, young people in the mental health system, and youth with physical disabilities. During adolescence, government programs have been a major part of their lives, yet eligibility for most programs typically ends between the ages of eighteen and twenty-one. This critical volume shows the unfortunate repercussions of this termination of support and points out the issues that must be addressed to improve these young people's chances of becoming successful adults.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSocial sciences. 0aYoung adults. 0aYouth with social disabilities. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aphysical disabilities, youth, mental health, students, special education, homelessness, runaway, foster care, juvenile justice, vulnerable populations, adu